The case for being there is understandable, yet could it possibly be that NOT being on LinkedIn will be a NET WIN for NS - ‚ÄúLinkedOut‚Äù over LinkedIn? Think so. Let me for a second oppose NS having much of a presence there - why:

LI is at this point an ATROCITY to humanity (or a net atrocity, if we recognize all the good things about it haha):

1) The way LinkedIn is set up and the nature of their user base encourages affectation/appearing to be something over actually being, and has played its part in forming a culture of meritless status and show-off over substance and earnest work. Surely this is a generalization, there are earnest people on LI, but there are too many that don‚Äôt seem so. Would think such a platform doesn‚Äôt deserve our presence or attention.

2) A minor thing that is telling of the spirit of this platform: The LI profile page format is ‚Äúvertical‚Äù, as if one‚Äôs work/life is a ladder from one thing to another. It‚Äôs a subtle thing, but I‚Äôve personally seen its subtle strong grip on the minds of many otherwise promising people. Anecdotally, I have friends that admit thinking all too much on how their next move is going to ‚Äúlook‚Äù on their Linkedin profile, which is sad. One could say it‚Äôs their personal weaknesses that are at the roots of this, but still, LI amplifies them. I wouldn‚Äôt want to fuel such a platform.

3) Many great people (surely not all) have left it already, never joined it in the first place, or almost never use it. Could say not being there is a a luxury for the particularly privileged, but would argue it‚Äôs a luxury we as a community can afford because we can recruit and spread the word in more powerful ways (1 to 1, Twitter, etc).

Would therefore say not being on LI is actually a NET-WIN for NS - we lose out a bit on reaching many at once, but we gain more by our absence from it, and by simply inviting our friends directly 1 on 1?
